@ForceMaximus84 Nah, it’s funny how people have been whipped into all having the same absurd opinion that Rian Johnson somehow “hates” Star Wars. TLJ angered some people because they didn’t want Luke to have any type of character arc. They just wanted him to be a happy-go-lucky badass with zero problems, who would instantly say “Let’s kick sum assss!” when the call to action came. But of course, that would be horrible storytelling, and Johnson knew that the Joseph Campbell Heroes Journey that the original Star Wars was based on needed The Rejection of the Call to Action, meaning Luke needed to be a reluctant- or initially openly antagonistic- hero, to be true to the fable. He follows Obi-Wan’s arc, even sacrificing himself to save the day, while becoming a Force Ghost. I know I didn’t love having to see Luke struggle, but it’s good storytelling.

Younger fans had these characters behind glass and untouchable, like their action figures, so they couldn’t stomach any actual drama or surprise. But let me tell you, when I walked out of Empire as a kid, I was angry and confused… where was the big fist-pump end?! What happened to Good Vs. Evil, now Darth Vader is Luke’s DAD?! And Luke cries and gets his hand chopped off??

It was a TOTAL mindf-ck… but audiences were stronger back in the day, and there was no industry of hating everything, so when the dust settled, everyone was happy Lucas took some crazy risks. Now I’m not saying TLJ is in the same league as Empire, but it was a movie clearly made by a talented superfan who wanted to give people that same reaction. And I respect that.

@TonyMaccey-yr3nv Ahhhh, you are a Rian Johnson fan. I can see why you came here then. I also noticed that Rian's movies are so great that you named none of them! Personally I thought The Brothers Bloom was a poorly written slog fest. Looper had consistancy problems, bad story writing, and a lack of decent charcter development. TLJ would take me hours to list all the problems. And Knives Out and The Glass Onion were complete garbage...  But if you liked all those movies, there is absolutely  nothing wrong with that. It means he connected with you, which I call a success for a movie. And no one even talked about financial viability, that is your strawman! 

 I also noticed you are big fan of the award shows, and actually put value on those awards... That is so adorable!!! Should I also list all the crap movies that have received awards over the years, to put that bad argument into perspective? I mean, all you have to do if fully defend Gigi, and you will  have defended awards. 

I also noticed that you talked about Will Jordan having best selling novels, but you are the first one to make this claim, so you can see where my confusion comes from.  I guess your point is that you are so worried about Jordan having a voice or an opinion that you want him silenced. Though I notice that you you are attacking him as writer as your excuse why he shouldn't be allowed to have an opinion, while you failed to point out what was wrong with any of his critiques or what was bad about his writting. Can I assumed you read his many books, and that is why you have so much to offer on the subject? That would actually be meaningful in the current conversation, which is why I ask. If you don't like the guy, then ignore him. Your outrage sounds rather petty, and I would actually assume you were more intelligent than that.

@TonyMaccey-yr3nv I started watching Logan because he is entertaining, and I really can't poke holes in most of his critiques. On the rare occasion I don't agree with him I will be vocal about it, but I wouldn't say I am a fanboy. I have a neutral feeling about it all. However, I didn't see where he was wrong once in this clip. He was a bit harsh on a couple points, but they were backed with decent evidence...

Like I said, I just can't say I have liked anything Rian has directed or wrote. The Breaking Bad looks good on his resume but he is in the sea of 25 different directors there. There are people who like the guy, and there is nothing wrong with that. Most don't do well defending him though, but I totally get it if his movies connect. There are some pretty bad movies out there that I connect with. And Art is Subjective.

I think most people here are a bit unfair with JJ Abrahams though. He is one of those writer directors that needs to write all 3 movies to get his payoff. You can't expect him to do 1 movie in a series! He doesn't have that range at all!

@HonsHon The force awakens was denounced as a retread. Playing it safe required they do something slightly less mechanical. So it's the fault of The Force Awakens that it might have given Johnson a license to be more 'creative'. But nothing about 'Brick' screamed 'Star Wars'. Johnson was an odd fit.

My nephews saw The Force Awakens before me. I saw them immediately afterwards. Their parents had told them not to spoil it. But they didn't have any irrepressible enthusiasm. A kid who had seen a film that sparked their imagination would struggle with the command not to talk about it. I remember the level of enthusiasm I felt after I saw 'Independence day' in theatre as a child. I expected them to be thinking 'whoosh' and '[light sabre activation noise]'. They seemed so calm - like they'd been sedated. So I thought it was a bad sign. After I saw it, I sat in the theatre. The families who had seen it trundled out. I didn't get a sense that anyone had been wowed. It left me cold. I was noticing seams in the plot. I was noticing noisy film direction that felt like it should be in a michael bay film.

The idea of getting a different director isn't necessarily a recipe for disaster. The Alien trilogy got Ridley Scott, James Cameron and David Fincher. But imagine living at a moment in time when the exciting directors were supposedly JJ and Rian Johnson.

@Mereologist 150% correct. TLJ was given nothing to work with except garbage. There was no way it would be decent. It had two movies worth of character building it had to do. Meanwhile, it wasn't allowed to contradict the prior movie that broke the vast majority of the prior canon.

Frankly, anyone who points to TLJ as the downfall, needs to rewatch TFA, they don't know what they are talking about.

Remember how before TLJ, the most common recommendation for the next movie was to make TFA a dream?

@kingnull2697 So, no.  You haven't seen it.  I know people are mad and disappointed and want someone to blame about how bad Star Wars was.  

But the truth is, Rian Johnson did make some good things.  That's why he got the job.

Black and white thinking where people are all good or all bad is usually a hallmark of immaturity.  But of course the internet "has one opinion" lol
